---
title: Shrimp Pad See Ew with Broccoli, Mushrooms, and Peanuts
description: In its native Thailand, pad see ew is always made to order and always in small quantities—never more than a few servings at a time. That’s not only so that it comes out sizzling and hot, but also so that all the ingredients have ample space to sear in the pan. Which is why this recipe is perfect for a quick dinner: as you’re tossing the rice noodles, sauce, shrimp, and aromatics, you can pretend you’re a Bangkok street-food hawker deftly whipping up a batch for a favorite customer.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/w17-r4-classic-08bdc725.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/w17-r4-classic-2d7689e4.pdf
author: HelloFresh
cuisine: North America
nutrition:
  calories: 730 kcal
  fat: 23 g
  saturated fat: 3 g
  carbohydrates: 96 g
  sugar: 13 g
  protein: 40 g
  fiber: 8 g
  sodium: 860 mg
course: main course
time required: 45 minutes
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/w17-r4-classic-58c2d8074f78db79e7218432
servings: 2
---

Wash and dry all produce. Bring a #large pot{} of @salted water{} to a boil. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @shallot{1}(halved, peeled, and thinly sliced). Thinly slice @garlic{2%cloves}(thinly sliced). Trim, then slice @button mushrooms{4%oz}(trimmed and sliced). Roughly chop @peanuts{1%oz}(roughly chopped). Peel @ginger{1%thumb}(peeled), then mince until you have 1 TSBP. Pick leaves from @basil{½%oz}(leaves picked) and tear into small pieces. Thinly slice @chili pepper{1}(thinly sliced).

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%tbsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add garlic to pan and cook until fragrant, about ~{30%seconds}. Add @broccoli florets{8%oz} and give it a toss. Pour in ½ cup @water{½%cup} and cook, tossing occasionally, until broccoli is tender, ~{4-5%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Remove from pan and set aside.

Heat another drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add mushrooms and cook, tossing, until softened and a few shades darker, ~{4-5%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper, then set aside with broccoli.

Once water is boiling, add @wide rice noodles{6%oz} to #pot{}. Remove from heat and let soak until al dente, ~{6-7%minutes}. (TIP: Stir noodles occasionally to prevent clumping.) Drain and rinse under cold water. Meanwhile, stir together @soy sauce{2%tbsp}, @sesame oil{½%tbsp} (we sent more), and @sugar{1%tbsp} in a #small bowl{}.

In same pan, heat another drizzle of oil. Add shallot and Thai chili (to taste). Cook until softened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Toss in ginger and @shrimp{10%oz} and cook until shrimp are starting to turn opaque, about ~{2%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper. Add rice noodles and soy sauce mixture to pan and toss to coat.

Add broccoli, mushrooms, and basil leaves to pan. Cook, tossing constantly, until shrimp are cooked through and everything is well combined, about ~{2%minutes} more. Divide between #bowls{} and sprinkle with peanuts.

> In its native Thailand, pad see ew is always made to order and always in small
> quantities—never more than a few servings at a time. That's not only so that it
> comes out sizzling and hot, but also so that all the ingredients have ample
> space to sear in the pan.

> This recipe is perfect for a quick dinner: as you're tossing the rice noodles,
> sauce, shrimp, and aromatics, you can pretend you're a Bangkok street-food
> hawker deftly whipping up a batch for a favorite customer.